# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: matroid-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] In matroid theory, the **dual** of a matroid M is another matroid $M^{\ast }$ that has the same elements as M , and in which a set is independent if and only if M has a basis set disjoint from it.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] Matroid duals go back to the original paper by Hassler Whitney defining matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] They generalize to matroids the notions of plane graph duality.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] Duality is an involution: for all M , $(M^{\ast })^{\ast }=M$ .
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] An alternative definition of the dual matroid is that its basis sets are the complements of the basis sets of M .
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] The basis exchange axiom, used to define matroids from their bases, is self-complementary, so the dual of a matroid is necessarily a matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] The flats of M are complementary to the cyclic sets (unions of circuits) of $M^{\ast }$ , and vice versa.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] If r is the rank function of a matroid M on ground set E , then the rank function of the dual matroid is $r^{\ast }(S)=r(E\setminus S)+|S|-r(E)$ .
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] A matroid minor is formed from a larger matroid M by two operations: the restriction $M\setminus x$ deletes element x from M without changing the independence or rank of the remaining sets, and the contraction $M/x$ deletes x from M after subtracting one from the rank of every set it belongs to.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] Thus, a minor of a dual is the same thing as a dual of a minor.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] An individual matroid is self-dual (generalizing e.g. the self-dual polyhedra for graphic matroids) if it is isomorphic to its own dual.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] The isomorphism may, but is not required to, leave the elements of the matroid fixed.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] Any algorithm that tests whether a given matroid is self-dual, given access to the matroid via an independence oracle, must perform an exponential number of oracle queries, and therefore cannot take polynomial time.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] Many important matroid families are self-dual, meaning that a matroid belongs to the family if and only if its dual does.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] Many other matroid families come in dual pairs.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] It is an open problem whether the family of algebraic matroids is self-dual.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] If *V* is a vector space and *V** is its orthogonal complement, then the linear matroid of *V* and the linear matroid of *V** are duals.
[src:matroid-theory/dual-matroid] As a corollary, the dual of any linear matroid is a linear matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] A **greedy algorithm** is an algorithm which, at each step, makes the choice that is locally optimal, and subsequently does not reconsider past choices.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Greedy algorithms are often used to solve combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] If an optimization problem only depends on the partial solution of solving it for one subproblem, we can solve this problem by "greedily" considering only the locally optimal subproblem.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] In this sense, a greedy algorithm is a special case of a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] In many cases, a greedy algorithm does not produce an exact solution, but can yield solutions that approximate an exact solution in a reasonable amount of time.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] An example of a problem which admits an exact greedy solution, the activity selection problem.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Given a collection of tasks which can be done between allotted time intervals, the problem is to determine the maximum number of tasks that can be done.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] A greedy algorithm in $O(n\log(n))$ which solves this problem sorts the tasks by the end time and then repeatedly chooses the first task that begins after the last task ended.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Many classic algorithms in computer science such as the Huffman coding algorithm, Prim's algorithm, Kruskal's algorithm, and Dijkstra's algorithm all use greedy properties in their design.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Mathematicians frequently use *greedy strategies* in proofs as well.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] A classic example is what Raphael Yuster refers to as the greedy proof that every tournament in graph contains a Hamiltonian path.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Since there is no formal definition of what a greedy algorithm is, a complete characterization of when a problem admits a greedy algorithm as a solution is not known.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] However, special cases have been identified.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Jack Edmonds showed that a greedy algorithm can be used to solve a class of linear combinatorial optimization problems with a matroid structure.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Later Bernhard Korte and László Lovász characterized a broader class of optimization problems by introducing the notion of a greedoid.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] This allowed, for example, a proof of the optimality of Prim's algorithm.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Algorithms which undo past steps are not greedy.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] For example, the Gale-Shapley algorithm is not a greedy algorithm since although it constructs a solution by choosing the current best pairing, in the process, existing solutions may be modified.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] One technique used to prove the optimiality of greedy algorithms is an exchange argument.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] The exchange argument demonstrates that any solution different from the greedy solution is at most as good as the greedy solution.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Conclude by induction that the greedy solution is optimal.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Starting from A, a greedy algorithm that tries to find the maximum by following the greatest slope will find the local maximum at "m", oblivious to the global maximum at "M".
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] To reach the largest sum, at each step, the greedy algorithm will choose what appears to be the optimal immediate choice, so it will choose 12 instead of 3 at the second step, and will not reach the best solution, which contains 99.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Graph theory is a rich source of greedy algorithms.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Computing scientists frequently use greedy algorithms frequently to compute graph invariants.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Greedy algorithms are also used to find upper bounds for the chromatic numbers.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] A simple example is the bound $\chi (G)\leq \Delta (G)+1$ obtained by a greedy algorithm.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] We begin by taking a vertex that has not been colored.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Since it has at most $\Delta (G)$ neighbours, at most $\Delta (G)$ colors are used in adjacent vertices, leaving a color free for the vertex under consideration.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] A solution to the NP-complete travelling salesman problem can be approximated by starting from an empty edge set and then adding the next cheapest edge which is a subgraph of a complete tour.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] This greedy algorithm has been proven to yield at most $\Theta (\log n)$ times longer than the optimal tour.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Another example is that a solution for the 0-1 knapsack problem can be approximated by using the greedy algorithm for the fractional knapsack problem.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] This greedy algorithm has been proven to yield a solution at least half the value of the optimal solution.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Solutions for submodular maximization are approximated using a greedy algorithm which yields a solution at least half the value of the optimal solution.
[src:matroid-theory/greedy-algorithm] Problems for which greedy algorithms are used to provide approximation algorithms include the set cover, load balancing, Steiner tree and independent set problem.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] In combinatorial optimization, the **matroid intersection** problem is to find a largest common independent set in two matroids over the same ground set.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] If the elements of the matroid are assigned real weights, the **weighted matroid intersection** problem is to find a common independent set with the maximum possible weight.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] These problems generalize many problems in graph theory and combinatorial optimization including finding maximum matchings and maximum weight matchings in bipartite graphs and finding arborescences in directed graphs.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] In other words, there is always a simple upper bound proof, consisting of a partitioning of the ground set amongst the two matroids, whose value (the sum of the respective ranks) equals the size of a maximum common independent set.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] Based on this theorem, the matroid intersection problem for two matroids can be solved in polynomial time using matroid partitioning algorithms.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] One may define a partition matroid *MU* on the ground set *E*, in which a set of edges is independent if no two of the edges have the same endpoint in *U*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] Similarly one may define a matroid *MV* in which a set of edges is independent if no two of the edges have the same endpoint in *V*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] Any set of edges that is independent in both *MU* and *MV* has the property that no two of its edges share an endpoint; that is, it is a matching.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] Thus, the largest common independent set of *MU* and *MV* is a maximum matching in *G*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] Similarly, if each edge has a weight, then the maximum-weight independent set of *MU* and *MV* is a Maximum weight matching in *G*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] There are several polynomial-time algorithms for weighted matroid intersection, with different run-times.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] In a variant of weighted matroid intersection, called "(Pk)", the goal is to find a common independent set with the maximum possible weight among all such sets with cardinality *k*, if such a set exists.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] This variant, too, can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] The matroid intersection problem becomes NP-hard when three matroids are involved, instead of only two.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] One proof of this hardness result uses a reduction from the Hamiltonian path problem in directed graphs.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] Given a directed graph *G* with *n* vertices, and specified nodes *s* and *t*, the Hamiltonian path problem is the problem of determining whether there exists a simple path of length *n* − 1 that starts at *s* and ends at *t*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] It may be assumed without loss of generality that *s* has no incoming edges and *t* has no outgoing edges.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] Another computational problem on matroids, the matroid parity problem, was formulated by Lawler as a common generalization of matroid intersection and non-bipartite graph matching.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] However, although it can be solved in polynomial time for linear matroids, it is NP-hard for other matroids, and requires exponential time in the matroid oracle model.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-intersection] The weighted matroid intersection problem is a special case in which the matroid valuations are constant, so we only seek to maximize $w(M)$ subject to *MX* is a base in *BX* and *MY* is a base in *BY* *.* Murota presents a polynomial-time algorithm for this problem.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In combinatorics, a **matroid** /ˈmeɪtrɔɪd/ is a structure that abstracts and generalizes the notion of linear independence in vector spaces.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] There are many equivalent ways to define a matroid axiomatically, the most significant being in terms of: independent sets; bases or circuits; rank functions; closure operators; and closed sets or *flats*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In the language of partially ordered sets, a finite simple matroid is equivalent to a geometric lattice.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Matroid theory borrows extensively from the terms used in both linear algebra and graph theory, largely because it is the abstraction of various notions of central importance in these fields.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Matroids have found applications in geometry, topology, combinatorial optimization, network theory, and coding theory.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] There are many equivalent ways to define a (finite) matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The first two properties define a combinatorial structure known as an independence system (or abstract simplicial complex).
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Actually, assuming (I2), property (I1) is equivalent to the fact that at least one subset of E is independent, i.e., ${\mathcal {I}}\neq \emptyset$ .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A subset of the ground set E that is not independent is called *dependent*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A maximal independent set – that is, an independent set that becomes dependent upon adding any element of E – is called a *basis* for the matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A *circuit* in a matroid M is a minimal dependent subset of E – that is, a dependent set whose proper subsets are all independent.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The term arises because the circuits of graphic matroids are cycles in the corresponding graphs.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The dependent sets, the bases, or the circuits of a matroid characterize the matroid completely: a set is independent if and only if it is not dependent, if and only if it is a subset of a basis, and if and only if it does not contain a circuit.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The collections of dependent sets, of bases, and of circuits each have simple properties that may be taken as axioms for a matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] This property (B2) is called the *basis exchange property*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] It follows from this property that no member of ${\mathcal {B}}$ can be a proper subset of any other.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] It is a basic result of matroid theory, directly analogous to a similar theorem of bases in linear algebra, that any two bases of a matroid M have the same number of elements.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] If M is a matroid on E , and A is a subset of E , then a matroid on A can be defined by considering a subset of A to be independent if and only if it is independent in M .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] This allows us to talk about *submatroids* and about the rank of any subset of E .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] These properties can be used as one of the alternative definitions of a finite matroid: If $(E,r)$ satisfies these properties, then the independent sets of a matroid over E can be defined as those subsets A of E with $r(A)=|A|$ .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In the language of partially ordered sets, such a matroid structure is equivalent to the geometric lattice whose elements are the subsets $A\subset M$ , partially ordered by inclusion.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The difference $|A|-r(A)$ is called the *nullity* of the subset A .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] It is the minimum number of elements that must be removed from A to obtain an independent set.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The nullity of E in M is called the nullity of M .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The difference $r(E)-r(A)$ is sometimes called the *corank* of the subset A .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Let M be a matroid on a finite set E , with rank function r as above.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The first three of these properties are the defining properties of a closure operator.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The fourth is sometimes called the *Mac Lane–Steinitz exchange property*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] These properties may be taken as another definition of matroid: every function $\operatorname {cl$ that obeys these properties determines a matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A set whose closure equals itself is said to be *closed*, or a *flat* or *subspace* of the matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A set is closed if it is maximal for its rank, meaning that the addition of any other element to the set would increase the rank.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The class ${\mathcal {L}}(M)$ of all flats, partially ordered by set inclusion, forms a matroid lattice.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Thus, the lattice of flats of this matroid is naturally isomorphic to L .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In a matroid of rank r , a flat of rank $r-1$ is called a *hyperplane*, or *co-atoms* or *copoints*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] These are the maximal proper flats; that is, the only superset of a hyperplane that is also a flat is the set E of all the elements of the matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] An equivalent definition is that a coatom is a subset of *E* that does not span *M*, but such that adding any other element to it does make a spanning set.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] He proved that there is a matroid for which C is the class of circuits and D is the class of cocircuits.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Conversely, if C and D are the circuit and cocircuit classes of a matroid M with ground set E , then $(E,C,D)$ is a graphoid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Thus, graphoids give a *self-dual cryptomorphic axiomatization* of matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The set of all subsets of E defines the independent sets of a matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Let E be a finite set and k a natural number.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] One may define a matroid on E by taking every k element subset of E to be a basis.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] This is known as the *uniform matroid* of rank k .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A uniform matroid with rank k and with n elements is denoted $U_{k,n}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] All uniform matroids of rank at least 2 are simple (see § Additional terms).
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The uniform matroid of rank 2 on n points is called the n *point line*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A matroid is uniform if and only if it has no circuits of size less than one plus the rank of the matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The direct sums of uniform matroids are called partition matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In the uniform matroid $U_{0,n}$ , every element is a loop (an element that does not belong to any independent set), and in the uniform matroid $U_{n,n}$ , every element is a coloop (an element that belongs to all bases).
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The direct sum of matroids of these two types is a partition matroid in which every element is a loop or a coloop; it is called a *discrete matroid*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] An equivalent definition of a discrete matroid is a matroid in which every proper, non-empty subset of the ground set E is a separator.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Matroid theory developed mainly out of a deep examination of the properties of independence and dimension in vector spaces.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The validity of the independent set axioms for this matroid follows from the Steinitz exchange lemma.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] An important example of a matroid defined in this way is the Fano matroid, a rank three matroid derived from the Fano plane, a finite geometry with seven points (the seven elements of the matroid) and seven lines (the proper nontrivial flats of the matroid).
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] It is a linear matroid whose elements may be described as the seven nonzero points in a three dimensional vector space over the finite field GF(2).
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] However, it is not possible to provide a similar representation for the Fano matroid using the real numbers in place of GF(2).
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A matrix A with entries in a field gives rise to a matroid M on its set of columns.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The dependent sets of columns in the matroid are those that are linearly dependent as vectors.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] For instance, the Fano matroid can be represented in this way as a 3 × 7 (0,1) matrix.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Column matroids are just vector matroids under another name, but there are often reasons to favor the matrix representation.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A matroid that is equivalent to a vector matroid, although it may be presented differently, is called *representable* or *linear*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] If M is equivalent to a vector matroid over a field F , then we say M is *representable over* F ; in particular, M is *real representable* if it is representable over the real numbers.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] For instance, although a graphic matroid (see below) is presented in terms of a graph, it is also representable by vectors over any field.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A basic problem in matroid theory is to characterize the matroids that may be represented over a given field $F;$ Rota's conjecture describes a possible characterization for every finite field.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A proof of Rota's conjecture was announced, but not published, in 2014 by Geelen, Gerards, and Whittle.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A regular matroid is a matroid that is representable over all possible fields.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The Vámos matroid is the simplest example of a matroid that is not representable over any field.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A second original source for the theory of matroids is graph theory.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Every finite graph (or multigraph) G gives rise to a matroid $M(G)$ as follows: take as E the set of all edges in G and consider a set of edges independent if and only if it is a forest; that is, if it does not contain a simple cycle.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Then $M(G)$ is called a *cycle matroid*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Matroids derived in this way are *graphic matroids*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Not every matroid is graphic, but all matroids on three elements are graphic.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A signed graph, whose edges are labeled by signs, and a gain graph, which is a graph whose edges are labeled orientably from a group, each give rise to a biased graph and therefore have frame and lift matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] , which equals the number of edges outside a maximal forest of that subgraph, and also the number of independent cycles in it.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A third original source of matroid theory is field theory.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A matroid that is equivalent to a matroid of this kind is called an algebraic matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The problem of characterizing algebraic matroids is extremely difficult; little is known about it.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The Vámos matroid provides an example of a matroid that is not algebraic.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] There are some standard ways to make new matroids out of old ones.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] If M is a finite matroid, we can define the *orthogonal* or *dual matroid* $M^{*}$ by taking the same underlying set and calling a set a *basis* in $M^{*}$ if and only if its complement is a basis in M .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] It is not difficult to verify that $M^{*}$ is a matroid and that the dual of $M^{*}$ is M .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The dual can be described equally well in terms of other ways to define a matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] According to a matroid version of Kuratowski's theorem, the dual of a graphic matroid M is a graphic matroid if and only if M is the matroid of a planar graph.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In this case, the dual of M is the matroid of the dual graph of G .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The dual of a vector matroid representable over a particular field F is also representable over F .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The dual of a transversal matroid is a strict gammoid and vice versa.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The cycle matroid of a graph is the dual matroid of its bond matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] If *M* is a matroid with element set *E*, and *S* is a subset of *E*, the *restriction* of *M* to *S*, written *M* |*S*, is the matroid on the set *S* whose independent sets are the independent sets of *M* that are contained in *S*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Its circuits are the circuits of *M* that are contained in *S* and its rank function is that of *M* restricted to subsets of *S*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In linear algebra, this corresponds to restricting to the subspace generated by the vectors in *S*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Equivalently if *T* = *M*−*S* this may be termed the *deletion* of *T*, written *M*\*T* or *M*−*T*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The submatroids of *M* are precisely the results of a sequence of deletions: the order is irrelevant.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The dual operation of restriction is contraction.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] If *T* is a subset of *E*, the *contraction* of *M* by *T*, written *M*/*T*, is the matroid on the underlying set *E* − *T* whose rank function is $r'(A)=r(A\cup T)-r(T)$ .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In linear algebra, this corresponds to looking at the quotient space by the linear space generated by the vectors in *T*, together with the images of the vectors in *E* − *T*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A matroid *N* that is obtained from *M* by a sequence of restriction and contraction operations is called a minor of *M*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Many important families of matroids may be characterized by the minor-minimal matroids that do not belong to the family; these are called *forbidden* or *excluded minors*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Let *M* be a matroid with an underlying set of elements *E*, and let *N* be another matroid on an underlying set *F*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The *direct sum* of matroids *M* and *N* is the matroid whose underlying set is the disjoint union of *E* and *F*, and whose independent sets are the disjoint unions of an independent set of *M* with an independent set of *N*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The *union* of *M* and *N* is the matroid whose underlying set is the union (not the disjoint union) of *E* and *F*, and whose independent sets are those subsets that are the union of an independent set in *M* and one in *N*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Usually the term "union" is applied when *E* = *F*, but that assumption is not essential.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] If *E* and *F* are disjoint, the union is the direct sum.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Let *M* be a matroid with an underlying set of elements *E*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Several important combinatorial optimization problems can be solved efficiently on every matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Two standalone systems for calculations with matroids are Kingan's Oid and Hlineny's Macek.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] "Oid" is an interactive, extensible software system for experimenting with matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] "Macek" is a specialized software system with tools and routines for reasonably efficient combinatorial computations with representable matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Both open source mathematics software systems SAGE and Macaulay2 contain matroid packages.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Maple has a package for dealing with matroids since the version 2024.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] There are two especially significant polynomials associated to a finite matroid *M* on the ground set *E*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Each is a *matroid invariant*, which means that isomorphic matroids have the same polynomial.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] where μ denotes the Möbius function of the geometric lattice of the matroid and the sum is taken over all the flats A of the matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The beta invariant is non-negative, and is zero if and only if M is disconnected, or empty, or a loop.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Otherwise it depends only on the lattice of flats of M .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] If M has no loops and coloops then $\beta (M)=\beta (M^{*})$ .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The *Whitney numbers of the first kind* of M are the coefficients of the powers of $\lambda$ in the characteristic polynomial.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The *Whitney numbers of the second kind* of M are the numbers of flats of each rank.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] That is, $W_{i}(M)$ is the number of rank i flats.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The Whitney numbers of both kinds generalize the Stirling numbers of the first and second kind, which are the Whitney numbers of the cycle matroid of the complete graph, and equivalently of the partition lattice.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] They were named after Hassler Whitney, the (co)founder of matroid theory, by Gian-Carlo Rota.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The name has been extended to the similar numbers for finite ranked partially ordered sets.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The *Tutte polynomial* of a matroid, $T_{M}(x,y)$ , generalizes the characteristic polynomial to two variables.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] which implies a number of dualities between properties of M and properties of $M^{*}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Another definition is in terms of internal and external activities and a sum over bases, reflecting the fact that $T(1,1)$ is the number of bases.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] This, which sums over fewer subsets but has more complicated terms, was Tutte's original definition.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] There is a further definition in terms of recursion by deletion and contraction.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] is said to be a *Tutte–Grothendieck invariant*.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The Tutte polynomial is the most general such invariant; that is, the Tutte polynomial is a Tutte–Grothendieck invariant and every such invariant is an evaluation of the Tutte polynomial.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The Tutte polynomial $T_{G}$ of a graph is the Tutte polynomial $T_{M(G)}$ of its cycle matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The theory of infinite matroids is much more complicated than that of finite matroids and forms a subject of its own.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] For a long time, one of the difficulties has been that there were many reasonable and useful definitions, none of which appeared to capture all the important aspects of finite matroid theory.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] For instance, it seemed to be hard to have bases, circuits, and duality together in one notion of infinite matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The simplest definition of an infinite matroid is to require *finite rank*; that is, the rank of *E* is finite.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] This theory is similar to that of finite matroids except for the failure of duality due to the fact that the dual of an infinite matroid of finite rank does not have finite rank.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Finite-rank matroids include any subsets of finite-dimensional vector spaces and of field extensions of finite transcendence degree.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The next simplest infinite generalization is finitary matroids, also known as pregeometries.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Equivalently, every dependent set contains a finite dependent set.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Examples are linear dependence of arbitrary subsets of infinite-dimensional vector spaces (but not infinite dependencies as in Hilbert and Banach spaces), and algebraic dependence in arbitrary subsets of field extensions of possibly infinite transcendence degree.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Again, the class of finitary matroid is not self-dual, because the dual of a finitary matroid is not finitary.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Finitary infinite matroids are studied in model theory, a branch of mathematical logic with strong ties to algebra.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In the late 1960s matroid theorists asked for a more general notion that shares the different aspects of finite matroids and generalizes their duality.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Many notions of infinite matroids were defined in response to this challenge, but the question remained open.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Higgs became known as *B-matroids* and was studied by Higgs, Oxley, and others in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] According to a recent result by Bruhn et al.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] (2013), it solves the problem: Arriving at the same notion independently, they provided five equivalent systems of axiom—in terms of independence, bases, circuits, closure and rank.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] The duality of B-matroids generalizes dualities that can be observed in infinite graphs.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Every subset of an independent set is independent.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] For every nonmaximal (under set inclusion) independent set I and maximal independent set J , there is $x\in J\smallsetminus I$ such that $I\cup \{x\}$ is independent.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] For every subset X of the base space, every independent subset I of X can be extended to a maximal independent subset of X .
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] With these axioms, every matroid has a dual.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Matroid theory was introduced by Whitney (1935).
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] It was also independently discovered by Takeo Nakasawa, whose work was forgotten for many years (Nishimura & Kuroda (2009)).
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In his seminal paper, Whitney provided two axioms for independence, and defined any structure adhering to these axioms to be "matroids".
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] His key observation was that these axioms provide an abstraction of "independence" that is common to both graphs and matrices.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Because of this, many of the terms used in matroid theory resemble the terms for their analogous concepts in linear algebra or graph theory.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Almost immediately after Whitney first wrote about matroids, an important article was written by MacLane (1936) on the relation of matroids to projective geometry.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] A year later, van der Waerden (1937) noted similarities between algebraic and linear dependence in his classic textbook on Modern Algebra.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In the 1940s Richard Rado developed further theory under the name "independence systems" with an eye towards transversal theory, where his name for the subject is still sometimes used.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Tutte became the foremost figure in matroid theory, a position he retained for many years.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] which are so complicated that later theorists have gone to great trouble to eliminate the need for them in proofs.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Crapo (1969) and Brylawski (1972) generalized to matroids Tutte's "dichromate", a graphic polynomial now known as the Tutte polynomial (named by Crapo).
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Their work has recently (especially in the 2000s) been followed by a flood of papers—though not as many as on the Tutte polynomial of a graph.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In 1976 Dominic Welsh published the first comprehensive book on matroid theory.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Paul Seymour's decomposition theorem for regular matroids (Seymour (1980)) was the most significant and influential work of the late 1970s and the 1980s.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Another fundamental contribution, by Kahn & Kung (1982), showed why projective geometries and Dowling geometries play such an important role in matroid theory.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] By the 1980s there were many other important contributors, but one should not omit to mention Geoff Whittle's extension to ternary matroids of Tutte's characterization of binary matroids that are representable over the rationals (Whittle 1995), perhaps the biggest single contribution of the 1990s.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] In the current period (since around 2000) the Matroid Minors Project of Geelen, Gerards, Whittle, and others, has produced substantial advances in the structure theory of matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid-theory] Many others have also contributed to that part of matroid theory, which (in the first and second decades of the 21st century) is flourishing.
[src:matroid-theory/matroid] These properties may be taken as another definition of matroid: every function $\operatorname {cl} :{\mathcal {P}}(E)\to {\mathcal {P}}(E)$ that obeys these properties determines a matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] An **oriented matroid** is a mathematical structure that abstracts the properties of directed graphs, vector arrangements over ordered fields, and hyperplane arrangements over ordered fields.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] In comparison, an ordinary (i.e., non-oriented) matroid abstracts the dependence properties that are common both to graphs, which are not necessarily *directed*, and to arrangements of vectors over fields, which are not necessarily *ordered*.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] All oriented matroids have an underlying matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Thus, results on ordinary matroids can be applied to oriented matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] However, the converse is false; some matroids cannot become an oriented matroid by *orienting* an underlying structure (e.g., circuits or independent sets).
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The distinction between matroids and oriented matroids is discussed further below.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Matroids are often useful in areas such as dimension theory and algorithms.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Because of an oriented matroid's inclusion of additional details about the *oriented* nature of a structure, its usefulness extends further into several areas including geometry and optimization.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The first appearance of oriented matroids was in a 1966 article by George J.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Minty and was confined to regular matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Rockafellar (1969) suggested the problem of generalizing Minty's concept to real vector spaces.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] His proposal helped lead to the development of the general theory.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] In order to abstract the concept of orientation on the edges of a graph to sets, one needs the ability to assign "direction" to the elements of a set.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The way this achieved is with the following definition of *signed sets*.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Given an element x of the support, we will write x for a positive element and $-x$ for a negative element.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] In this way, a signed set is just adding negative signs to distinguished elements.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] This will make sense as a "direction" only when we consider orientations of larger structures.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Then the sign of each element will encode its direction relative to this orientation.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Like ordinary matroids, several equivalent systems of axioms exist.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Let ${\mathcal {C}}$ be a collection of *signed sets*, each of which is *supported* by a subset of E .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] If the following axioms hold for ${\mathcal {C}}$ , then equivalently ${\mathcal {C}}$ is the set of *signed circuits* for an *oriented matroid* on E .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The *vectors* of an oriented matroid are the compositions of circuits.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The *covectors* of an oriented matroid are the vectors of its dual oriented matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The term *chirotope* is derived from the mathematical notion of chirality, which is a concept abstracted from chemistry, where it is used to distinguish molecules that have the same structure except for a reflection.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Every chirotope of rank r gives rise to a set of bases of a matroid on E consisting of those r -element subsets that $\chi$ assigns a nonzero value.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The chirotope can then sign the circuits of that matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Thus a chirotope gives rise to the *oriented bases* of an oriented matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] In this sense, (B0) is the nonempty axiom for bases and (B2) is the basis exchange property.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Oriented matroids are often introduced (e.g., Bachem and Kern) as an abstraction for directed graphs or systems of linear inequalities.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Given a digraph, we define a signed circuit from the standard circuit of the graph by the following method.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The support of the signed circuit $\textstyle {\underline {X}}$ is the standard set of edges in a minimal cycle.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] We go along the cycle in the clockwise or anticlockwise direction assigning those edges whose orientation agrees with the direction to the positive elements $\textstyle X^{+}$ and those edges whose orientation disagrees with the direction to the negative elements $\textstyle X^{-}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] If $\textstyle {\mathcal {C}}$ is the set of all such $\textstyle X$ , then $\textstyle {\mathcal {C}}$ is the set of signed circuits of an oriented matroid on the set of edges of the directed graph.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] If we consider the directed graph on the right, then we can see that there are only two (graph) circuits, namely $\textstyle \{(1,2),(1,3),(3,2)\}$ and $\textstyle \{(3,4),(4,3)\}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] This is opposed to the ordinary directed graphic matroid for the same graph, whose only circuit is $\textstyle \{(3,4),(4,3)\}$ , as the other edges cannot form a directed cycle without flipping the direction of some of them.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] If $\textstyle E$ is any finite subset of $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , then the set of minimal linearly dependent sets forms the circuit set of a matroid on $\textstyle E$ .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] with $\textstyle \lambda _{i}\in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The set of all such $\textstyle X$ forms the set of signed circuits of an oriented matroid on $\textstyle E$ .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Oriented matroids that can be realized this way are called representable.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Given the same set of vectors E , we can define the same oriented matroid with a chirotope $\chi :E^{r}\rightarrow \{-1,0,1\}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] where the right hand side of the equation is the sign of the determinant.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Then $\chi$ is the chirotope of the same oriented matroid on the set E .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] A real hyperplane arrangement ${\mathcal {A}}=\{H_{1},\ldots ,H_{n}\}$ is a finite set of hyperplanes in $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , each containing the origin.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] By picking one side of each hyperplane to be the positive side, we obtain an arrangement of half-spaces.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] A half-space arrangement breaks down the ambient space into a finite collection of cells, each defined by which side of each hyperplane it lands on.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] That is, assign each point $x\in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ to the signed set $X=(X^{+},X^{-})$ with $i\in X^{+}$ if x is on the positive side of $H_{i}$ and $i\in X^{-}$ if x is on the negative side of $H_{i}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] This collection of signed sets defines the set of covectors of the oriented matroid, which are the vectors of the dual oriented matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Each rank-3 oriented matroid is equivalent to an arrangement of pseudolines, and each oriented matroid which is also *uniform* is equivalent to a **simple** pseudoline arrangement (where every 2 lines cross exactly once, and no 3 lines cross at the same point).
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Tools for dealing with one form can therefore be used to analyze its equivalent form for either study.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Ziegler introduces oriented matroids via convex polytopes.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] A standard matroid is called *orientable* if its circuits are the supports of signed circuits of some oriented matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] It is known that all real representable matroids are orientable.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] It is also known that the class of orientable matroids is closed under taking minors, however the list of forbidden minors for orientable matroids is known to be infinite.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] In this sense, oriented matroids is a much stricter formalization than regular matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Just as a matroid has a unique duals, an oriented matroid has a unique dual, often called its "orthogonal dual".
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] What this means is that the underlying matroids are dual and that the cocircuits are signed so that they are "orthogonal" to every circuit.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Two signed sets are said to be *orthogonal* if the intersection of their supports is empty or if the restriction of their positive elements to the intersection and negative elements to the intersection form two nonidentical and non-opposite signed sets.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The existence and uniqueness of the dual oriented matroid depends on the fact that every signed circuit is orthogonal to every signed cocircuit.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] To see why orthogonality is necessary for uniqueness one needs only to look to the digraph example above.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] We know that for planar graphs the dual of the circuit matroid is the circuit matroid of the graph's planar dual.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Thus there are as many different dual pairs of oriented matroids based on the matroid of the graph as there are ways to orient the graph and in a corresponding way its dual.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] To see the explicit construction of this unique orthogonal dual oriented matroid, consider an oriented matroid's chirotope $\chi :E^{r}\rightarrow \{-1,0,1\}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] If we consider a list of elements of $x_{1},\dots ,x_{k}\in E$ as a cyclic permutation then we define $\operatorname {sgn} (x_{1},\dots ,x_{k})$ to be the sign of the associated permutation.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] then $\chi ^{*}$ is the chirotope of the unique orthogonal dual oriented matroid.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Not all oriented matroids are representable—that is, not all have realizations as point configurations, or, equivalently, hyperplane arrangements.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] However, in some sense, all oriented matroids come close to having realizations as hyperplane arrangements.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] In particular, the **Folkman–Lawrence topological representation theorem** states that any oriented matroid has a realization as an arrangement of pseudospheres.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] A d -dimensional *pseudosphere* is an embedding of $e:S^{d}\hookrightarrow S^{d+1}$ such that there exists a homeomorphism $h:S^{d+1}\rightarrow S^{d+1}$ so that $h\circ e$ embeds $S^{d}$ as an equator of $S^{d+1}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] In this sense a pseudosphere is just a tame sphere (as opposed to wild spheres).
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] A *pseudosphere arrangement in $S^{d}$* is a collection of pseudospheres that intersect along pseudospheres.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Finally, the Folkman–Lawrence topological representation theorem states that every oriented matroid of rank $d+1$ can be obtained from a pseudosphere arrangement in $S^{d}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] It is named after Jon Folkman and Jim Lawrence, who published it in 1978.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The theory of oriented matroids has influenced the development of combinatorial geometry, especially the theory of convex polytopes, zonotopes, and configurations of vectors (equivalently, arrangements of hyperplanes).
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Many results—Carathéodory's theorem, Helly's theorem, Radon's theorem, the Hahn–Banach theorem, the Krein–Milman theorem, the lemma of Farkas—can be formulated using appropriate oriented matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The development of an axiom system for oriented matroids was initiated by R.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Tyrrell Rockafellar to describe the sign patterns of the matrices arising through the pivoting operations of Dantzig's simplex algorithm; Rockafellar was inspired by Albert W.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Tucker's studies of such sign patterns in "Tucker tableaux".
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] The theory of oriented matroids has led to breakthroughs in combinatorial optimization.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] In linear programming, it was the language in which Robert G.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Bland formulated his pivoting rule, by which the simplex algorithm avoids cycles.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Similarly, it was used by Terlaky and Zhang to prove that their criss-cross algorithms have finite termination for linear programming problems.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Similar results were made in convex quadratic programming by Todd and Terlaky.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] It has been applied to linear-fractional programming, quadratic-programming problems, and linear complementarity problems.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Outside of combinatorial optimization, oriented matroid theory also appears in convex minimization in Rockafellar's theory of "monotropic programming" and related notions of "fortified descent".
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] Similarly, matroid theory has influenced the development of combinatorial algorithms, particularly the greedy algorithm.
[src:matroid-theory/oriented-matroid] More generally, a greedoid is useful for studying the finite termination of algorithms.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The **Tutte polynomial**, also called the **dichromate** or the **Tutte–Whitney polynomial**, is a graph polynomial.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] It is a polynomial in two variables which plays an important role in graph theory.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] It is defined for every undirected graph G and contains information about how the graph is connected.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The importance of this polynomial stems from the information it contains about G .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] It is also the source of several central computational problems in theoretical computer science.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The Tutte polynomial has several equivalent definitions.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] It is essentially equivalent to Whitney’s **rank polynomial**, Tutte’s own **dichromatic polynomial** and Fortuin–Kasteleyn’s **random cluster model** under simple transformations.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] It is essentially a generating function for the number of edge sets of a given size and number of connected components, with immediate generalizations to matroids.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] It is also the most general graph invariant that can be defined by a deletion–contraction recurrence.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Several textbooks about graph theory and matroid theory devote entire chapters to it.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] In this definition it is clear that $T_{G}$ is well-defined and a polynomial in x and y .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The same definition can be given using slightly different notation by letting $r(A)=|V|-k(A)$ denote the rank of the graph $(V,A)$ .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Tutte’s original definition of $T_{G}$ is equivalent but less easily stated.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] where $t_{ij}$ denotes the number of spanning trees of *internal activity* i and *external activity* j .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] A third definition uses a **deletion–contraction recurrence**.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The edge contraction $G/uv$ of graph G is the graph obtained by merging the vertices u and v and removing the edge $uv$ .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] We write $G-uv$ for the graph where the edge $uv$ is merely removed.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] if G contains i bridges and j loops and no other edges.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Especially, $T_{G}=1$ if G contains no edges.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The **random cluster model** from statistical mechanics due to Fortuin & Kasteleyn (1972) provides yet another equivalent definition.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The Tutte polynomial factors into connected components.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Especially, the chromatic polynomial of a planar graph is the flow polynomial of its dual.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Tutte refers to such functions as **V-functions**.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Isomorphic graphs have the same Tutte polynomial, but the converse is not true.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] For example, the Tutte polynomial of every tree on m edges is $x^{m}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Tutte polynomials are often given in tabular form by listing the coefficients $t_{ij}$ of $x^{i}y^{j}$ in row i and column j .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Tutte’s interest in the deletion–contraction formula started in his undergraduate days at Trinity College, Cambridge, originally motivated by perfect rectangles and spanning trees.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] He often applied the formula in his research and “wondered if there were other interesting functions of graphs, invariant under isomorphism, with similar recursion formulae.” R.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Foster had already observed that the chromatic polynomial is one such function, and Tutte began to discover more.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] His original terminology for graph invariants that satisfy the deletion–contraction recursion was *W-function*, and *V-function* if multiplicative over components.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Independently of the work in algebraic graph theory, Potts began studying the partition function of certain models in statistical mechanics in 1952.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The work by Fortuin and Kasteleyn on the random cluster model, a generalisation of the Potts model, provided a unifying expression that showed the relation to the Tutte polynomial.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] At various points and lines of the $(x,y)$ -plane, the Tutte polynomial evaluates to quantities that have been studied in their own right in diverse fields of mathematics and physics.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Part of the appeal of the Tutte polynomial comes from the unifying framework it provides for analysing these quantities.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] where $k(G)$ denotes the number of connected components of *G*.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] For integer λ the value of chromatic polynomial $\chi _{G}(\lambda )$ equals the number of vertex colourings of *G* using a set of λ colours.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] It is clear that $\chi _{G}(\lambda )$ does not depend on the set of colours.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] What is less clear is that it is the evaluation at λ of a polynomial with integer coefficients.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] If *G* contains a loop (a single edge connecting a vertex to itself), then $\chi _{G}(\lambda )=0$ .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The three conditions above enable us to calculate $\chi _{G}(\lambda )$ , by applying a sequence of edge deletions and contractions; but they give no guarantee that a different sequence of deletions and contractions will lead to the same value.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The guarantee comes from the fact that $\chi _{G}(\lambda )$ counts something, independently of the recurrence.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] gives the number of acyclic orientations.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Along the hyperbola $xy=1$ , the Tutte polynomial of a planar graph specialises to the Jones polynomial of an associated alternating knot.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] $T_{G}(2,1)$ counts the number of forests, i.e., the number of acyclic edge subsets.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] $T_{G}(1,1)$ counts the number of spanning forests (edge subsets without cycles and the same number of connected components as *G*).
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] If the graph is connected, $T_{G}(1,1)$ counts the number of spanning trees.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] $T_{G}(1,2)$ counts the number of spanning subgraphs (edge subsets with the same number of connected components as *G*).
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] $T_{G}(2,0)$ counts the number of acyclic orientations of *G*.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] $T_{G}(0,2)$ counts the number of strongly connected orientations of *G*.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] counts the number of Eulerian orientations of *G*.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Here $k(G)$ is the number of connected components of *G*.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] If *G* is the *m* × *n* grid graph, then $2T_{G}(3,3)$ counts the number of ways to tile a rectangle of width 4*m* and height 4*n* with T-tetrominoes.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] the Tutte polynomial specialises to the partition function, $Z(\cdot ),$ of the Ising model studied in statistical physics.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] then the Tutte polynomial specialises to the partition function of the *q*-state Potts model.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Various physical quantities analysed in the framework of the Potts model translate to specific parts of the $H_{q}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] At $x=0$ , the Tutte polynomial specialises to the flow polynomial studied in combinatorics.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] For a connected and undirected graph *G* and integer *k*, a nowhere-zero *k*-flow is an assignment of “flow” values $1,2,\dots ,k-1$ to the edges of an arbitrary orientation of *G* such that the total flow entering and leaving each vertex is congruent modulo *k*.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The flow polynomial $C_{G}(k)$ denotes the number of nowhere-zero *k*-flows.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] At $x=1$ , the Tutte polynomial specialises to the all-terminal reliability polynomial studied in network theory.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] For a connected graph *G* remove every edge with probability *p*; this models a network subject to random edge failures.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Then the reliability polynomial is a function $R_{G}(p)$ , a polynomial in *p*, that gives the probability that every pair of vertices in *G* remains connected after the edges fail.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Tutte also defined a closer 2-variable generalization of the chromatic polynomial, the **dichromatic polynomial** of a graph.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] where $k(A)$ is the number of connected components of the spanning subgraph (*V*,*A*).
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The dichromatic polynomial does not generalize to matroids because *k*(*A*) is not a matroid property: different graphs with the same matroid can have different numbers of connected components.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The Martin polynomial $m_{\vec {G}}(x)$ of an oriented 4-regular graph ${\vec {G}}$ was defined by Pierre Martin in 1977.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] immediately yields a recursive algorithm for computing it for a given graph: as long as you can find an edge *e* that is not a loop or bridge, recursively compute the Tutte polynomial for when that edge is deleted, and when that edge is contracted.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Then add the two sub-results together to get the overall Tutte polynomial for the graph.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The base case is a monomial $x^{m}y^{n}$ where *m* is the number of bridges, and *n* is the number of loops.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The analysis can be improved to within a polynomial factor of the number $\tau (G)$ of spanning trees of the input graph.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] For sparse graphs with $m=O(n)$ this running time is $\exp(O(n))$ .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] so the deletion–contraction algorithm runs within a polynomial factor of this bound.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] In practice, graph isomorphism testing is used to avoid some recursive calls.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] This approach works well for graphs that are quite sparse and exhibit many symmetries; the performance of the algorithm depends on the heuristic used to pick the edge *e*.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] In some restricted instances, the Tutte polynomial can be computed in polynomial time, ultimately because Gaussian elimination efficiently computes the matrix operations determinant and Pfaffian.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] These algorithms are themselves important results from algebraic graph theory and statistical mechanics.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] $T_{G}(1,1)$ equals the number $\tau (G)$ of spanning trees of a connected graph.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] This is computable in polynomial time as the determinant of a maximal principal submatrix of the Laplacian matrix of *G*, an early result in algebraic graph theory known as Kirchhoff’s Matrix–Tree theorem.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Likewise, the dimension of the bicycle space at $T_{G}(-1,-1)$ can be computed in polynomial time by Gaussian elimination.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] For planar graphs, the partition function of the Ising model, i.e., the Tutte polynomial at the hyperbola $H_{2}$ , can be expressed as a Pfaffian and computed efficiently via the FKT algorithm.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] This idea was developed by Fisher, Kasteleyn, and Temperley to compute the number of dimer covers of a planar lattice model.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Using a Markov chain Monte Carlo method, the Tutte polynomial can be arbitrarily well approximated along the positive branch of $H_{2}$ , equivalently, the partition function of the ferromagnetic Ising model.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] This exploits the close connection between the Ising model and the problem of counting matchings in a graph.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The idea behind this celebrated result of Jerrum and Sinclair is to set up a Markov chain whose states are the matchings of the input graph.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The transitions are defined by choosing edges at random and modifying the matching accordingly.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The resulting Markov chain is rapidly mixing and leads to “sufficiently random” matchings, which can be used to recover the partition function using random sampling.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The resulting algorithm is a fully polynomial-time randomized approximation scheme (fpras).
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Several computational problems are associated with the Tutte polynomial.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] In particular, the output allows evaluating $T_{G}(-2,0)$ which is equivalent to counting the number of 3-colourings of *G*.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] This latter question is #P-complete, even when restricted to the family of planar graphs, so the problem of computing the coefficients of the Tutte polynomial for a given graph is #P-hard even for planar graphs.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The hardness of these problems varies with the coordinates $(x,y)$ .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] If both *x* and *y* are non-negative integers, the problem $T_{G}(x,y)$ belongs to #P.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] For general integer pairs, the Tutte polynomial contains negative terms, which places the problem in the complexity class GapP, the closure of #P under subtraction.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] To accommodate rational coordinates $(x,y)$ , one can define a rational analogue of #P.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The computational complexity of exactly computing $T_{G}(x,y)$ falls into one of two classes for any $x,y\in \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] in which cases it is computable in polynomial time.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] If the problem is restricted to the class of planar graphs, the points on the hyperbola $H_{2}$ become polynomial-time computable as well.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] All other points remain #P-hard, even for bipartite planar graphs.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] In his paper on the dichotomy for planar graphs, Vertigan claims (in his conclusion) that the same result holds when further restricted to graphs with vertex degree at most three, save for the point $T_{G}(0,-2)$ , which counts nowhere-zero **Z**3-flows and is computable in polynomial time.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] These results contain several notable special cases.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] For example, the problem of computing the partition function of the Ising model is #P-hard in general, even though celebrated algorithms of Onsager and Fisher solve it for planar lattices.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Also, the Jones polynomial is #P-hard to compute.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Finally, computing the number of four-colorings of a planar graph is #P-complete, even though the decision problem is trivial by the four color theorem.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] In contrast, it is easy to see that counting the number of three-colorings for planar graphs is #P-complete because the decision problem is known to be NP-complete via a parsimonious reduction.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] The question of which points admit a good approximation algorithm has been very well studied.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Apart from the points that can be computed exactly in polynomial time, the only approximation algorithm known for $T_{G}(x,y)$ is Jerrum and Sinclair’s FPRAS, which works for points on the “Ising” hyperbola $H_{2}$ for *y* > 0.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] If the input graphs are restricted to dense instances, with degree $\Omega (n)$ , there is an FPRAS if *x* ≥ 1, *y* ≥ 1.
[src:matroid-theory/tutte-polynomial] Even though the situation is not as well understood as for exact computation, large areas of the plane are known to be hard to approximate.
